n white Jews and Black Americans, Black Power activists enabled Jewish activists to devise a new Judeo-centered political agenda—including the emancipation of Soviet Jews, the rise of Jewish Day Schools, the revitalization of worship services with gender-inclusive liturgy, and the birth of a new form of American Zionism.Undermining widely held beliefs about the civil rights movement, Black Power, racism, Soviet Jewry, American Zionism, and the religious revival of the 1970s, Black Power, Jewish Politics describes a new political consensus based on identity politics that drew Black and Jewish Americans together and altered the course of American liberalism.In the midst of national reckoning on race, this revised edition extends the book’s thesis to the contemporary period, investigating the limits of white Jewish liberalism, the ways in which scholars have and have not addressed racial privilege in their work, and the dynamics around these themes in a much more diverse American Jewish community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with Jews2DLC. 0aBlack powerzUnited States2DLC. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aJewszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh1 aKaufman, Ilana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075164240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479826988.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479826988423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479826988/original  a978-3-11-075164-2  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles